<!doctype html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8"><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"><title>Russell Dudek | USAA Process Automation Candidate Vision</title><meta name="description" content="An independent candidate vision for governed process automation at USAA by Russell Dudek."><link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css"></head><body><a class="skip" href="#main">Skip to content</a><header class="site-header"><nav class="nav" aria-label="Primary"><a class="candidate-id" href="index.html">Russell Dudek</a><button class="menu-btn" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="nav-links">Menu</button><div class="nav-links" id="nav-links"><a href="#mandate">Mandate</a><a href="#model">Operating model</a><a href="#evidence">Evidence</a><a href="#entry">120 days</a><a href="resume.html" class="nav-primary">Resume</a></div></nav></header><main id="main">
<section class="hero"><div class="hero-inner"><div class="employer-lockup"><img src="assets/brand/usaa-logo-official.png" alt="USAA"><div class="employer-copy">Independent candidate vision<strong>Director, Process Excellence - Process Automation</strong>by Russell Dudek</div></div><div class="hero-grid"><div><h1>Scale the workflow <span>and its assurance</span> together.</h1><p class="hero-lead">The mandate is not simply to automate more work. It is to build a portfolio in which member value, employee flow, control evidence, and operating ownership improve as one system.</p><div class="hero-proof"><span>Member friction</span><span>Process intelligence</span><span>Risk by design</span><span>Measurable value</span></div><a class="hero-action" href="#model">Explore the Automation Assurance Twin</a></div>
<div class="twin-shell" id="hero-twin"><div class="twin-title"><span>Automation Assurance Twin</span><span class="decision-chip" id="hero-decision">Automate + standardize</span></div><div class="twin-plane work-plane"><h3>Work plane - what changes for the member and employee</h3><div class="plane-track"><i class="track-signal"></i><div class="plane-stage">Need</div><div class="plane-stage">Work</div><div class="plane-stage">Decision</div><div class="plane-stage">Outcome</div></div></div><div class="twin-links"><i></i><i></i><i></i><i></i></div><div class="twin-plane assurance-plane"><h3>Assurance plane - what makes the automation trustworthy</h3><div class="plane-track"><i class="track-signal"></i><div class="plane-stage">Owner</div><div class="plane-stage">Authority</div><div class="plane-stage">Evidence</div><div class="plane-stage">Monitoring</div></div></div><div class="twin-readout"><div class="readout-copy"><strong id="hero-state">Synchronized for scale</strong><span id="hero-explain">Stable rules, visible exceptions, named ownership, and instrumented control evidence.</span></div><div class="sync-meter" aria-hidden="true"><i></i><i></i><i></i><i></i></div></div></div></div></div></section>
<section class="section" id="mandate"><div class="section-inner moment-grid"><div><div class="kicker">Why this role matters now</div><h2>Member value is becoming an operating discipline.</h2><p class="section-intro">USAA's 2025 Annual Report describes a deliberate focus on simplifying digital experiences, improving claims processing, reducing paperwork, and making the enterprise work more seamlessly for members. It also created a Member Value organization to anticipate needs and remove friction.</p><div class="moment-stat"><strong>14 million+</strong><span>members served across insurance, banking, and retirement solutions - a scale at which local automation choices become enterprise operating choices.</span></div></div><div><div class="pressure-list"><div class="pressure-row"><strong>Faster service vs. stronger control</strong><p>Automation must reduce repetitive effort without weakening evidence, exception handling, or human accountability.</p></div><div class="pressure-row"><strong>Enterprise standards vs. business reality</strong><p>A COE needs reusable governance while respecting legitimate variation across insurance, banking, claims, service, and shared functions.</p></div><div class="pressure-row"><strong>Platform scale vs. process truth</strong><p>RPA and workflow tools amplify whatever process logic they are given. Process intelligence must precede tool enthusiasm.</p></div><div class="pressure-row"><strong>Savings vs. realized member value</strong><p>A business case is incomplete until the benefit appears in cycle time, quality, service, risk, adoption, or another named outcome.</p></div></div></div></div></section>
<section class="section section-dark" id="model"><div class="section-inner"><div class="kicker">Candidate thesis</div><h2>The Automation Assurance Twin</h2><p class="section-intro">Every automation candidate should have two synchronized views: the work plane that changes the member or employee experience, and the assurance plane that defines ownership, authority, evidence, monitoring, and fallback. Scale only when both are ready.</p><div class="model-layout"><aside class="scenario-panel"><h3>Test the decision</h3><p>Illustrative scenarios for discovery - not claims about USAA's internal processes.</p><div class="scenario-buttons" role="tablist" aria-label="Automation scenarios"><button role="tab" aria-selected="true" data-scenario="stable">Stable high-volume rules</button><button role="tab" aria-selected="false" data-scenario="exception">Cross-system exception flow</button><button role="tab" aria-selected="false" data-scenario="human">Judgment-heavy member moment</button><button role="tab" aria-selected="false" data-scenario="evidence">Weak control evidence</button></div><p class="model-note">Keyboard: Tab to a scenario, then press Enter or Space. Reset by selecting the first scenario.</p></aside><div class="model-stage"><div class="twin-shell" id="model-twin"><div class="twin-title"><span>Illustrative decision state</span><span class="decision-chip" id="model-decision">Automate + standardize</span></div>